{
  "$schema": "https://json.schemastore.org/sarif-2.1.0.json",
  "version": "2.1.0",
  "runs": [
    {
      "tool": {
        "driver": {
          "name": "PMD",
          "version": "7.22.0",
          "informationUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/latest/",
          "rules": [
            {
              "id": "ShortClassName",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Avoid short class names like Date"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\nShort Classnames with fewer than e.g. five characters are not recommended.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_codestyle.html#shortclassname",
              "help": {
                "text": "\nShort Classnames with fewer than e.g. five characters are not recommended.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Code Style",
                "priority": 4,
                "tags": [
                  "Code Style"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "note"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CommentRequired",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Class comments are required"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\nDenotes whether javadoc (formal) comments are required (or unwanted) for specific language elements.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_documentation.html#commentrequired",
              "help": {
                "text": "\nDenotes whether javadoc (formal) comments are required (or unwanted) for specific language elements.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Documentation",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Documentation"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "GodClass",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Possible God Class (WMC=57, ATFD=17, TCC=6.667%)"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\nThe God Class rule detects the God Class design flaw using metrics. God classes do too many things,\nare very big and overly complex. They should be split apart to be more object-oriented.\nThe rule uses the detection strategy described in \"Object-Oriented Metrics in Practice\".\nThe violations are reported against the entire class.\n\nThe rule uses metrics to implement its detection strategy. The violation message\ngives information about the values of these metrics:\n* WMC: a class complexity measure, see {% jdoc java::lang.java.metrics.JavaMetrics#WEIGHED_METHOD_COUNT %}\n* ATFD: a measure of how much data external data the class uses, see {% jdoc java::lang.java.metrics.JavaMetrics#ACCESS_TO_FOREIGN_DATA %}\n* TCC: a measure of how tightly related the methods are, see {% jdoc java::lang.java.metrics.JavaMetrics#TIGHT_CLASS_COHESION %}\n\nThe rule identifies a god class by looking for classes which have all of the following properties:\n* High WMC\n* High ATFD\n* Low TCC\n\nSee also the reference:\n\nMichele Lanza and Radu Marinescu. *Object-Oriented Metrics in Practice:\nUsing Software Metrics to Characterize, Evaluate, and Improve the Design\nof Object-Oriented Systems.* Springer, Berlin, 1 edition, October 2006. Page 80.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_design.html#godclass",
              "help": {
                "text": "\nThe God Class rule detects the God Class design flaw using metrics. God classes do too many things,\nare very big and overly complex. They should be split apart to be more object-oriented.\nThe rule uses the detection strategy described in \"Object-Oriented Metrics in Practice\".\nThe violations are reported against the entire class.\n\nThe rule uses metrics to implement its detection strategy. The violation message\ngives information about the values of these metrics:\n* WMC: a class complexity measure, see {% jdoc java::lang.java.metrics.JavaMetrics#WEIGHED_METHOD_COUNT %}\n* ATFD: a measure of how much data external data the class uses, see {% jdoc java::lang.java.metrics.JavaMetrics#ACCESS_TO_FOREIGN_DATA %}\n* TCC: a measure of how tightly related the methods are, see {% jdoc java::lang.java.metrics.JavaMetrics#TIGHT_CLASS_COHESION %}\n\nThe rule identifies a god class by looking for classes which have all of the following properties:\n* High WMC\n* High ATFD\n* Low TCC\n\nSee also the reference:\n\nMichele Lanza and Radu Marinescu. *Object-Oriented Metrics in Practice:\nUsing Software Metrics to Characterize, Evaluate, and Improve the Design\nof Object-Oriented Systems.* Springer, Berlin, 1 edition, October 2006. Page 80.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Design",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Design"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CommentRequired",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Field comments are required"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\nDenotes whether javadoc (formal) comments are required (or unwanted) for specific language elements.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_documentation.html#commentrequired",
              "help": {
                "text": "\nDenotes whether javadoc (formal) comments are required (or unwanted) for specific language elements.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Documentation",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Documentation"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "LongVariable",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Avoid excessively long variable names like NORMALIZED_DATE_FORMATTER"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\nFields, formal arguments, or local variable names that are too long can make the code difficult to follow.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_codestyle.html#longvariable",
              "help": {
                "text": "\nFields, formal arguments, or local variable names that are too long can make the code difficult to follow.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Code Style",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Code Style"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "LongVariable",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Avoid excessively long variable names like SIMPLE_DATE_FORMATS"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\nFields, formal arguments, or local variable names that are too long can make the code difficult to follow.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_codestyle.html#longvariable",
              "help": {
                "text": "\nFields, formal arguments, or local variable names that are too long can make the code difficult to follow.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Code Style",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Code Style"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "LocalVariableCouldBeFinal",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Local variable 'formatStrings' could be declared final"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\nA local variable assigned only once can be declared final.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_codestyle.html#localvariablecouldbefinal",
              "help": {
                "text": "\nA local variable assigned only once can be declared final.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Code Style",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Code Style"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CommentSize",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Comment is too large: Line too long"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\nDetermines whether the dimensions of non-header comments found are within the specified limits.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_documentation.html#commentsize",
              "help": {
                "text": "\nDetermines whether the dimensions of non-header comments found are within the specified limits.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Documentation",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Documentation"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "AvoidFieldNameMatchingTypeName",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "It is somewhat confusing to have a field name matching the declaring class name"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\nIt is somewhat confusing to have a field name matching the declaring type name.\nThis probably means that type and/or field names should be chosen more carefully.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_errorprone.html#avoidfieldnamematchingtypename",
              "help": {
                "text": "\nIt is somewhat confusing to have a field name matching the declaring type name.\nThis probably means that type and/or field names should be chosen more carefully.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Error Prone",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Error Prone"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "UnusedPrivateField",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Avoid unused private fields such as 'endDate'."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\nDetects when a private field is declared and/or assigned a value, but not used.\n\nSince PMD 6.50.0 private fields are ignored, if the fields are annotated with any annotation or the\nenclosing class has any annotation. Annotations often enable a framework (such as dependency injection, mocking\nor e.g. Lombok) which use the fields by reflection or other means. This usage can't be detected by static code analysis.\nPreviously these frameworks where explicitly allowed by listing their annotations in the property\n\"ignoredAnnotations\", but that turned out to be prone of false positive for any not explicitly considered framework.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_bestpractices.html#unusedprivatefield",
              "help": {
                "text": "\nDetects when a private field is declared and/or assigned a value, but not used.\n\nSince PMD 6.50.0 private fields are ignored, if the fields are annotated with any annotation or the\nenclosing class has any annotation. Annotations often enable a framework (such as dependency injection, mocking\nor e.g. Lombok) which use the fields by reflection or other means. This usage can't be detected by static code analysis.\nPreviously these frameworks where explicitly allowed by listing their annotations in the property\n\"ignoredAnnotations\", but that turned out to be prone of false positive for any not explicitly considered framework.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Best Practices",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Best Practices"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CommentRequired",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Public method and constructor comments are required"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\nDenotes whether javadoc (formal) comments are required (or unwanted) for specific language elements.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_documentation.html#commentrequired",
              "help": {
                "text": "\nDenotes whether javadoc (formal) comments are required (or unwanted) for specific language elements.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Documentation",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Documentation"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "MethodArgumentCouldBeFinal",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Parameter 'year' is not assigned and could be declared final"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\n            Reports method and constructor parameters that can be made final because they are never reassigned within the body of the method.\n\n            This rule ignores unused parameters so as not to overlap with the rule {% rule java/bestpractices/UnusedFormalParameter %}.\n            It will also ignore the parameters of abstract methods.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_codestyle.html#methodargumentcouldbefinal",
              "help": {
                "text": "\n            Reports method and constructor parameters that can be made final because they are never reassigned within the body of the method.\n\n            This rule ignores unused parameters so as not to overlap with the rule {% rule java/bestpractices/UnusedFormalParameter %}.\n            It will also ignore the parameters of abstract methods.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Code Style",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Code Style"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "MethodArgumentCouldBeFinal",
